<DOC><DOCNO> AP880702-0184 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 0104EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a f BC-Week'sBusiness Adv02-03 1stadd 07-02 0459</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Week's Business, Adv 02-03, 1st add,0475</SECOND><HEAD>NEW YORK: with us.''</HEAD><TEXT>   In other business news this past week:   _Grain and soybean futures swung wildly in heavy trading on theChicago Board of Trade because of the drought, which has raised theprospect of higher food prices and hurt the farm equipment business.   _The Index of Leading Economic Indicators, the government'schief economic forecasting gauge, dipped 0.1 percent in May, butanalysts said the decline did not suggest a threat to economicgrowth at least for the rest of the year.   _Reports on the interest-rate sensitive construction industrysuggested a mixed picture. One said existing home sales rose 3.1percent in May while sales of new homes edged down 0.3 percent.Another report said construction spending climbed 1.1 percent inMay.   _U.S. factory orders for manufactured goods fell 0.6 percent inMay, but analysts weren't concerned, attibuting the drop to adecline in demand for aircraft, which fluctuates from month tomonth.   _A Commerce Department report showed the United Stateslengthened its lead as the largest debtor nation in 1987, when theU.S. foreign debt burden climbed to $368.2 billion, up 36.8 percentfrom 1986.   _The Senate Labor Committee approved legislation to raise thefederal minimum wage to $4.55 per hour from the current $3.35 overthe next three years.   _The Supreme Court issued a key civil rights ruling allowingemployees to use statistical evidence to prove their bosses areguilty of illegal discrimination. The justices also ruled defensecontractors enjoy broad protection from lawsuits.   _International Business Machines Corp. announced a $600 millionconsolidation plan it said would probably result in the resignationor retirement of 3,000 to 4,000 employees.   _An Airbus A320 jetliner crashed during a demonstration flightin France, and airline analysts said the accident could lead tocancelled orders and lost sales for the European consortium thatmakes the highly-touted plane.   _Directors of two big companies approved management-ledleveraged buyouts, transactions financed with borrowed money repaidthrough earnings and asset sales. Paper-products giant Fort HowardCorp. will become a private company in a $4.08 billion leveragedbuyout, while Payless Cashways will go private in a $909 milliondeal.   _Federal officials have extended until Aug. 1 the negotiatingdeadline for Texas billionaire Robert M. Bass, who is seeking totake over troubled American Savings and Loan Association, thenation's second largest thrift.   _Motown Records, which launched the careers of such blacksingers as Diana Ross, Michael Jackson and Stevie Wonder, was soldto MCA Inc. and an investment banking firm for $61 million.   _A former Continental Illinois National Bank andamp; Trust Co. officerand an ex-banker from Oklahoma accused of contributing toContinental's 1984 near-collapse pleaded guilty to criminal charges.</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions July 2-3</NOTE></DOC>